            <Title>Morality</Title>
            <Text>Morality.
 	

5 PCE - late in the summer

Anchorage Saturday Market - TIME MACHINE FOR PEACE market research booth...
                                                                                                    

Some time into the visitor's peace process:

The Brave Soul hesitated, then asked if she could ask a personal question. The individual consented.

	'So what's your angle?'
	'My angle. ? Like, my selfish reason for attempting to invent a world piece computer?'
	'Yeah, your selfish angle.'

The individual thought for a minute, mentally deliberating. Should he divulge? He relented:

	'I suffer from chronic mental illness, and I believe I have a high likelihood of developing Alzheimers in old age.'

The reception, and corresponding pause, the stare, waiting. The individual elaborated.

	'I need it for myself, to unify my inner fragments--my inner pieces--into a whole. I need my personal world piece computer. Every time my world piece computer goes offline or falters, things get really really bad for me. But I don't have the strength to maintain my world piece computer alone on my own, so I need help. This is why I need to make this into a social invention project. I am very sick. I need the help of this technology and of others. I need your help, which is why I am even talking to you. I am here to assimilate your wisdom.'

She stood there staring for a moment, considering, then gently exclaimed,

	'I think, that's.. powerful.'

Shifting uncomfortably, a wave of emotion, the individual replied,

	'Well it's the truth. It's my reality. I need this...'

The individual waved hands around the booth's tent's space, gesturing like it was a much larger object than it was,

	'...I cannot survive without it, without this. For me this is a deeply existential concern.'

The individual let out a massive sigh, crumpling, melting, humility. The individual went on,

	'And my grandpa had Alzheimers. I got to experience the progression as an observer, to experience how his personality eroded over time. It's an ugly disease. I think it is hands down the ugliest disease, besides perhaps dementia. It is the opposite of other diseases, the individual is the entity that erodes, not the body. And it is not a nice experience--things get ugly. I am at risk for Alzheimers and must erect a system that can manage all the pieces in my world, even if my faculties to act as a singular free agent erode, if my personality erodes. If I contract Alzheimers, I will have my world piece computer to help me remember things and stay focused, to help my self keep from fragmenting into frustration and anger and rage, to help prevent my individual image and legacy and dignity from disintegrating in front of my loved ones. I could rant about this for hours certainly, but I think you get my point.'

The Brave Soul responded,

	'Thank you for your candor.'
	'It's my...pleasure.'
	'I think you could really reach people with that.'
	'I don't know, but I sure hope so, cause it's coming out.'

And they carried on with the market booth universal piece--the peace process--conversing about peace in the context of a global computational peace system.

&lt;&lt; light teal paperclip &gt;&gt;
                                                                                                    

Later in the summer:

This Brave Soul was obviously well educated and well off. He read the large cardboard sign propped front and center with a smile, then looked up at the individual watching him from behind the front door-table.

	'Any thoughts? Feedback?'
	'No, no, I really don't want to step on your toes.'
	'Oh, no issue, it's ok, I happened to wear my steel-toe boots today!'

A stupid grin that elicited a big grin.

	'So go on!'
	'It won't work--'

The Brave Soul was expecting some sort of a counter attack or something.

	'--any of it. It just won't.'

But inquisition was all he found.

	'Umm, ok sure, that's a pretty strong statement, but would you care to elaborate?'

The Brave Soul read aloud the statement framed in black from the cardboard sign perched up against the market booth's table:

THE MOST I CAN DO IS START A CONVERSATION! ...I HOPE IT TURNS INTO MOVEMENT TOWARD HUMAN SOLIDARITY &amp; UNITY...

	'The social invention project to invent the world piece computer. Ok, sure. Problem is, any time there is a social movement with good intention, people inevitably take that movement and distort it, perverting its original good essence in one way or another. This project you propose will be no different.'

The individual thought for a moment. Then a few pieces clicked into place within the universal piece:

	'Well, for one, I said movement, not a movement. What I'm describing is more like a collective of individuals all doing their own thing, as individual  free agents, just following a set of universal rules that have the emergent effect of networking world piece computers. The overall movement itself will have evolution baked in, as part of the universal ruleset, so in principle it will always be one step ahead of the perversion and distortion. But yes, I agree, we Humans will always pervert and distort the good, I mean it's etched into the negative aspect of our Human Nature!'

The universal piece was running smoothly, rapport building. The Brave Soul was in the sunlight and he was clearly uncomfortable in his tucked in collared shirt and undershirt, perspiration on his forehead, hot. That piece exchange was clearly worth suffering the discomfort. 

	'Ok, so then what's your business model? How will you and your non-movement be supporting yourselves with this?'
	'That's one of the hard questions...'

The Brave Soul snickered.

	'...I have a high-level long-term notion, but nothing concrete in the immediate-term. Ultimately the revenue that funds the universal piece computer and its participants' livelihoods will revolve around big data sales and world piece computer manufacturing and production--a peace industry running parallel to the preexisting global economy, but indelibly tied to it by virtue of outsourcing.'

The Brave Soul shifted and cocked his head. It was time to lay down some weight:

	'Ok, I mean more like, how are you sustaining yourself now?'
	'Oh. I'm living off savings and trying to raise money as a conceptual peace artist.'
	'And... how is that going?'
	'Not very well! haha'
	'So what happens when you run out of money?'
	'I go back to electrical engineering, or maybe I teach myself blockchain engineering.'
	'Electrical engineering. ?!!'
	'Yeah, I have a degree in electrical engineering, I was working in telecom before this. I retired though, cause I got tired of it.'
	'Ok. Now you have my attention. I work in big data analytics, multiple advanced degrees. Yadda yadda, not important. You could call me a life learner.'
	'Hah! Kindred spirits!. Yeah, so, like, I'm serious about inventing computers; ideally the world piece computer will contain many electronic extensions and components, comprising a proper computer manufacturing enterprise.'
	'Hm. Let me take your card. I'll get back to you. I really gotta get going though, wife is calling.'

The individual handed a shitty business car over to this powerhouse of a Brave Soul. He felt sheepish. After-all, the QR code on it contained within its black and white bits, a field designating FAX NUMBER, YOUR MOM. The Brave Soul continued,

	'--oh! And take this pen, you'll love it, government issue--literally best pen you can find, and they are all made by blind people, nation's largest employer of the blind. My name's Pattrikc...'

The individual extended his hand.

	'...and you must be Blair.'
	'In the flesh.'
	'I'll be in touch; best of luck to you!'

The Brave Soul bolted off and left before having a chance to suffer the paperclip routine of the universal piece. In those moments afterward, the individual fixated on the recurring difficult problem: how would he or anybody else sustain themselves in the social invention effort? The simmer and smolder of inner conflict felt apparent. This was a hard problem and things weren't going well financially for the individual. Selling button pins with funny symbols or t-shirts at a market booth would never sustain. The psychological pressure of economic hardship with yet again failing mental health was settling in. The Individual chose a paperclip anyway for the Brave Soul.

&lt;&lt; gold matte clip &gt;&gt;
                                                                                                    

Even later in the summer:

He leaned in close, intimidating. Another man, a Brave Soul, this one short and stocky, with a black hole for a gaze. Voice low and serious, piercing like the gaze,

	'So are you a psychopath or something? You've gotta be a psychopath. This is the boldest exhibit I have seen, maybe ever. Look around at this display of originality, just in. your. face. Who are you. ? You on meds? You gotta be on meds. What kind of meds do you take?'
	'No. --not now. I'm Blair. My only label is my name. I am just an individual like anybody else. Like you.'
	'No, no, no...you know what you are?'
	'...What's that. ?'

The individual was working hard to stay focused, keep cool. The individual had no idea who this man was, nor what he was capable of. It seemed like a potentially volatile, potentially scary situation, a wildcard. The individual braced for impact.

	'You are what I call an unexpected event.'
	'Huh.'

Ok, not so bad. The individual followed up.

	'Well I certainly agree. I certainly wasn't expecting to become this, to experience anything at all for that matter. It's a real trip, this reality thing.'
	'You got that right.'

Uncomfortable shifting, staring.

	'Ok listen, Blair, now you just move your stool to the left right here. I'm going to interview you and film it with my camera.'

Impact!

	'Ooo...uh..., I am not sure if I feel comfortable with that, I mean, I really don't know you man.'
	'What are you afraid that I'll expose you? And post this recording on the internet and everybody will ridicule you ???
	'Hahahaha, well, yes, but then again, no. You can't expose me, for I am already exposed...'

The individual was feeling increasingly reckless as the summer went on, so the individual relented and filmed an impromptu recorded interview with a complete stranger. The surrounding busy market slowed to a halt, seemingly frozen in time outside the time machine for peace booth. It got heavy as fuck. Later on in the interview, the Brave Soul,

	'And this is my parting gift to you, the distillation of my entire life's belief system and experience.'

The individual hardened. This was the moment. It was time to assimilate wisdom, and a lifetime at the sound of it. The individual lived for these moments, having experienced hundreds over a lifetime's travels. Straight addicted.

	'Ok, hit me, I will carry it with me, incorporate it into the time machine for peace social invention project.'

The Brave Soul seemed relieved, validated,

	'Ok. Everything--the entire universe--boils down to three fundamental principles. Ready? :

The individual sat, staring, perhaps another wildcard, but it wasn't:

	1) state of being,
	2) individual free will, and
	3) morality.

The individual repeated:

	'State of being.
	 Individual free will.
	 Morality.'

A pause.

	'Ok, explain.'

The Brave Soul leaned in,

	'State of being is when you come online, you are aware and conscious.
	'Individual free will is when you recognize that you have a choice in the way you face reality.
	'Morality is the way that you face reality.
	'That's it, everything, it all boils down to that.'

The individual took a moment to encode the information into his memory palace.

	'Thank you. That is a lot to take in. I appreciate the simplicity though. Elegant.'

...

They parted ways, friends, warm.

&lt;&lt; white paperclip &gt;&gt;
                                                                                                    

The end of the summer:

A woman and her husband stopped by the booth, two Brave Souls.

The individual was feeling down about things, and the weather was cold and rainy too.

The two Brave Souls read the sign. The setup that day was minimal--just the two main signs, mainly to keep out of the rain because the tent was leaky, but mainly because the individual was growing tired. He acknowledged their presence with a warm gaze.

The woman stepped up:

	'I just want to share what I think will be crucial for this project to really take hold:'

The individual piqued, lurching up like a hyena, ears perked:

	'Please.'
	'We need to focus on improving education more than we actually are, and we simultaneously need to focus on getting women--especially mothers--into positions of political power. No woman with children will entertain sending other women's children to war. They just won't do it. I've been involved in education and politics my entire life and that's just what I've seen, it's what I know. Get mothers into positions of power. Your project depends on it.'

Fuck yes. This is what the individual was looking for. The booth was paying massive dividends.

	'Wow..thank you, I honestly had never thought of that..'

Though the individual could think of a couple pathological cases where that could be false, it seemed like sound reasoning otherwise. As she kept speaking he kept nodding intently. He never broke eye contact when people were sharing their wisdom. It was too valuable to miss a single expression. The man stepped up alongside here; she deliberately relinquished control of the conversation. This was obviously a coordinated performance. The two Brave Souls were a cohesive unit, no doubt.

	'See this on my wallet?'

Si vis pacem, para bellum.

	'I don't know Latin. What does it mean?'

The man leaned in,

	'If you want peace, prepare for war...'

Ah. The individual was deeply familiar with the concept. The individual explained that this was not a new idea in his world. In fact, the idea was fundamental. The male Brave Soul proceeded to deliver a monologue:

	'I am a retired military intelligence officer in the Navy. Did it my whole life, and still regularly consult. Let me assure you, from what I've known, for the foreseeable future at least, there will always be bad people who want to kill and harm others, people who want to cause war, people who want to exert their unbending will on the innocent and the vulnerable.'

The individual was thrilled to meet someone so grounded, responding,

	'So far you and I are in complete agreement.'

The eyes locked, two worlds completely connected. The individual nodding yet again, intently. The male Brave Soul continuing, his female Brave Soul counterpart nodding and staring in unison, injecting here and there. They were clearly a unified pair:

	'So then I'm sure you see that the reason for the global arms race in general is for the same reason you wouldn't sleep peacefully in your home if your front door was unlocked and open all the time. There are bad people out there, there likely always will be, even when the police are there to protect you. To ensure domestic peace and tranquility by the constitution, we have to be prepared for any international or domestic adversary. If not, how could you and your family sleep peacefully at night knowing that at any moment a foreign army or criminal super-cartel could invade and start laying waste to your home land, your home? How could you feel at peace if there were not a governmental monopoly on violence, where at any moment a group a bad people could get a hold of some weaponry and start persecuting some other group of the population, maybe that group being you and your kind?'

These were difficult and important questions. He continued,

	'How can you as an individual feel at peace in volatile situations if you know that you are incapable of physically defending yourself, without help at least? The sense of insecurity is the opposite of peace, and the peace of security demands preparing to meet intruding adversaries with violent force. We use police for this in most cases, and you dial 911 if you are incapable of protecting yourself from an adversary forcefully intruding into your world. But the world doesn't have a police force. So we prepare for war. Likewise, police often take a long time to arrive, minutes at best. To feel genuinely secure, you must be prepared to defend yourself until the police arrive.

Further,

	'Even if we declare some global entity as having the monopoly on violence over planet Earth, we will still need national military forces for temporary self-defense, because the global super-police will likewise take time to respond. Even if we invent some technology or operation that made it impossible for Humans to do violence, we would find that a large proportion of the population would not consent due to fear that they wouldn't be able to defend themselves. The only recourse there would be to force them to undergo the operation against their will, and that would be wrong, authoritarian, eugenic even.

The individual was intimately familiar with this line of reasoning. He embraced it. Humans will almost certainly always have violence (though perhaps in the inconceivable future we overcome that). We just need to prepare for war in better ways, and wage our wars in safer ways, with fewer casualties. The man concluded,

	'My point is, we will always need to be prepared to do violence. Otherwise the truly evil people in this world will exploit the lack of preparedness to systematically do unthinkable things to vulnerable people. To stop preparing for violence would be to concede and declare evil people as the official authoritarian rulers of the world, the monopoly of violence would belong to them. Until we figure out how to make bad people not exist--which is almost certainly impossible--we must prepare for war. This is the principle of deterrence.'

The individual looked back and forth at the older couple, nodding in deep contentment, a deep hardening of the face, stern, then a rather maniacal grin spreading across the face. It struck the individual in that moment, the immense gravity of the task at hand, the challenge of 'world peace', heavy shit, heavier than heavy. Speaking, 

	'You and I are in clear alignment thank you for presenting that so eloquently, and validating the perspective by sharing your experience. Ok. So, education and women in politics, and be prepared for violent adversaries. That's my takehome in a nutshell. You two seem from elsewhere, are you just visiting?'

They smiled as if hoping the individual would call them out; they were all ready to relax and be pleasant after such a heavy exchange.

	'Yeah, we're from New Jersey. This is Mrak, and I'm Shonann!'

Big smiles, and a round of handshakes.
	
	'I am thrilled to meet you, and that you stopped by the booth!'
	'Likewise!'
	
The paperclip routined executed.

Finally, the male Brave Soul made a statement:

	'You know, I really commend you. You have this massive mountain ahead of you. It will be a very hard and dangerous journey, and you have a very long way to go. You probably will not succeed.'

The individual broke into a big smile with lightly watering eyes.

	'I feel like I haven't even made it past the foothills. I know I will probably never succeed like I want. But I am an aspiring mountaineer, so who knows, maybe I'll learn what I need to make it to the top on my way to the top.'
	'It will take time friend. And much effort. But if you persist, I think you really have something good here. Trust me, I've seen it all, the good and the evil. I think you're on to something. I wish the very best of luck to you and hope to hear of you in the future.'

The shook hands and bade farewell. The individual concluded that aspect of the peace process, feeling the weight of it all looming.

&lt;&lt; maroon and grey paperclips &gt;&gt;
                                                                                                    

The end of the last piece exchange, the same day, rainy and wet:

It felt like two hours at least had gone by. The booth in a funny sense, did become a time machine every time the individual had a conversation about peace. Everything slowed down.

	'Ok, so say your project takes off and blows up...
...chances are you get assassinated.'

A pause.

	'I know.'

Silence among the group...

	'...so why do you persist? I don't get it.'

The individual deliberated within. Thinking was getting harder and harder as his illness progressed, and now he just felt an impulsive rant beginning to lurch within: lurch.

	'Listen, you wanna know why? I'm tired of this fucking shit. I'm tired of all this fucking shit. I don't care for this world. If you beg to differ, then I will accuse you of taking the privilege you have for granted. Like, take a fucking look around, things are NOT ok. Your notions of progress--society's notions--are marginal at best. I just want to mould this world into something that I actually want to live in for a change. I want to see significant change.
	'And I just wanna have a good time and do cool shit and get laid like anybody else. Like, I'll even take it a step further: I want to have only the best times, to do the coolest most epic shit, and have only the best lays. I want to feel the deepest love. Like, I'm probably just jaded. My standards are simply a lot higher than anything capable of being offered here, in this world. Most people are complacent. They experience sub-optimal and call it the good life.
	'Now, my problem is I can't kill myself, because bad things will happen to me if I do and I can't hurt my family. So to be honest, don't really care if someone assassinates me. That would be a relief and only further my cause. Besides, until we have the universal piece computer in perfect form--which is probably not possible--I will always exist. I am the individual who defines themself strictly in terms of the global pursuit of peace, treating peace as a computational process, the only way.
	'There will be many more instances of my individuality in the future. We will live forever. So go on, kill me. I'm gunna do some epic shit and have some epic experience and have a great time living life until then.'

Much of the rant really wasn't true in an absolute sense--it was super maniacal, and extremely ironic--but The Individual was under incredible mental pressure and in a nearly constant state of inner war at this point in the summer. The war spilled out right then in the middle of a space devoted to peace. Very awkward. They were all staring. The individual thought some more, recognized the hole being dug, then adjusted course, less self-centered,

	'But maybe more importantly, I think it's just important, important for our existence as a species. Like, it's grandiose but I really mean it. You said so yourself, that you believe we will annihilate ourselves, and that we should all just focus on having a good time and cherishing our loved ones--don't waste energy on changing things--don't waste energy on finding a way to systematically violate the second law, the ever-increasing state of entropy in the universe. A fool's errand you said.
	'What I propose is a way I believe we can do both--prevent self-annihilation and have a great time in the process. I don't see anybody else attempting what I am aspiring toward, so I have to assume I am alone. I have to try. I call it The Human Imperative. We need this. My intention is still to have a good time, so even if I fail, or get assassinated, it was at least fun, a real fucking trip. I have to hold onto hope though for the grand us. Life's too shitty without hope for our species.'

The individual caught themself, preferring not to ramble and rant any longer. Their brain wasn't working very well. Reeling in. The weight again. The gravity of the epic quest that lay ahead. It was looming. Heaviness. The mind was 

They talked more. It was fruitful, cordial, enjoyable, but something about the conversation left the individual unsettled. Maybe it was the assassination talk, or maybe it was the direct confrontation with a highly-intelligent, highly-convincing nihilist testing resolve. Who knows.

After they terminated the clip process, that was it:

The individual packed up all the pieces in the booth, loaded up the tent and totes in his truck. and never returned to the marketplace that summer.

Non-electronic digital memory segment number 149. The end.

&lt;&lt; dark green, yellow, light teal paperclips &gt;&gt;
                                                                                                    

Afterward:

There was the second dark age prior to then, and this particular market research program on the individual's behalf was an attempt at sparking a renaissance in the world piece computer invention effort.

But at that point, the individual's peace process--the universal piece and world piece computer--was shaky to begin with; something about the process was programmed incorrectly, or perhaps it was missing some vital component that the inventor just couldn't figure out. The market research and development booth was erected from a place of profound instability. It was doomed from the beginning.

A final thrust was the tipping point, a humiliating effort to crowdfund world piece computer invention under the time machine for peace. A spectacular effort to a whimpering failure. Eventually the individual's universal piece--having become progressively buggier and less reliable over time--completely collapsed, the personal world piece computer and peace process completely shutting down, a fatal error, a complete system crash. Those that knew the individual were not sure if the hardware was recoverable, or if the operating system and software had been wiped blank in the graceless exit. It was ugly.

There simply wasn't enough social support to maintain the individual's primitive peace process in such a deteriorated mindstate. The individual needed help but had none.

So marked the beginning of the last dark age in the Piece Computer Era.

The year was 5 PCE.
 	

7 PCE

I discovered that I had not been accepting responsibility. I was living with a god-mode mentality, but only from a place of fear and profound mental unwellness. I cannot bear any more dark ages. I will not bear another dark age. Another dark age would break me. My will cannot be broken.

During my recovery from the last dark age, I found I still struggled with violent ideations, intense emotions, wild and confusing thoughts. Pain deep in the soul. Exhaustion deep in the soul. Mental illness is no fucking joke. This last road of recovery was long.

The world piece computer invention project was my only saving force and grace coming out of that last dark age. But the project has caused me immeasurable pain over the the past seven years. Or maybe that was just my fear clouding my vision. how could I know. It was very much a love-hate relationship.

One day however, I discovered that I could just stop living in fear, mainly by facing my fears in written and spoken form, with acceptance and humility. It doesn't need to be trapped in my head. So I started to write it all out.

After writing for a while--probably 50,000 words--I encountered a lightbulb moment: I didn't need to suffer all the time. I am deeply privileged. I have the resources and the wherewithal to just get the help I need be ok if I want to. I am blessed in that regard. I just wasn't accepting responsibility for my inner world and what I need to do in this life.

So it struck me: individual free will means nothing without a morality, and morality is a choice. The reason I was suffering was all along that I was not submitting my will to the fact that I need others to survive. I cannot live this alone. My morality prior to this moment was a morality that believed it was ok to act in terms of individual pride, fear, and lonesomeness. Or maybe I just didn't know it was fear. Doesn't really matter.

Interestingly though, it seems that once the right morality is chosen, it no longer becomes a choice. That is, the morality must be followed, because it becomes a necessary aspect of survival. The morality wasn't really a choice, it was just what that individual needs to survive--their identity, that is--oftentimes even their physical form.

So for me, the universal piece is not a choice. The universal prosperity mission is not a choice. The five rules are not a choice. I live it because I need it. The world piece computer invention effort is still is a saving force for me, but now it is not the only force. The other individuals around me, those devoted to the same Human Imperative, those contributors to the time machine for peace, they are all saving forces each of their own. I rely on them. Some of us rely on each other.

I have a responsibility to see this through. And I need your help. We need your help.
                                                                                                    

And so it was, The Individual was born, passing from the maturation stage into the final stage of life, adult phase.

The Individual was finally ready to procreate. But this individual did not yet believe in physical procreation (though this was always a tempting option).

The Individual believed that the only way for individual agents of peace to take hold and erect and maintain a computational global peace system was to live forever. This is because The Individual believed peace is a never-ending evolutionary process, even certainly past the end of time (however that works). To accomplish immortality, The Individual hatched a plan. He sought to create a network of like-minded individuals, individuals whom like himself would pass through maturation phase and become like him, but their own, devoted to realizing The Human Imperative

These Individuals--their individual pieces--would be devoted to building the universal piece computer, so to erect and maintain the global peace system, ultimately coordinating the time machine for peace, the social invention program. Their prosperity mission was to use the universal piece computer to maximize the state of Human global peace, by using world piece computers to maximize the state of inner peace within Human Individuals and people. All this of course, while simultaneously minimizing their state of inner war. This was often referred to as the Human optimization problem. How do we best arrange all the pieces in the Human universe, so to achieve the prosperity mission?

As it turned out, The Individual was, in fact, alone in the world. There were a few like him in spirit, just not with this particular spirit, nor that particular vision and strategy. But one would suppose this is to be expected from individuals like so. They really just needed a lingua franca, a unifying glue.

To this end, it would only be a matter of time before other Individuals like him, became him. Or The Individual became them. Who knew. Or, they all become one Individual--The Individual--with no real personal preference or orientation. All just stewards of the universal piece. Until then, it was that absurd dude named Blair from Alaska.

Besides for the fun of it and for experimentation with others, The Individual by definition had no ego. The Individual was two parts: id, and superego--animalistic emotion and the inner voice of impartial reason, the manifestation of The Human Imperative. The Individual's constitution was the universal piece; The Individual was devoted solely to The Human Imperative. There is only one. There may be many bodies, many perspectives, many different experiences, many unique personalities, but The Individual numbers only one.

As it stands, as long as Humanity persists, The Individual will live forever, for we will always need to treat peace as an evolutionary computational process.

There will always be people who put computational peace above all else--people who treat peace first as a process, not a result. There will always be people dissatisfied with the state of global peace. Those people who mean it, they will inevitably become The Individual, too.

The Individual is not a movement. The Individual is made up of however many independent free agents there exist devoted to The Human Imperative.

The end times begin: the final push to satisfy The Human Imperative.
                                                                                                    

The Human Imperative:

Integrate Human experience to invent a way to overcome Humanity's greatest adversary: time.

To do so, create a social invention program devoted to this end.

The first objective is to invent the universal piece computer, a global peace system, to maintain a peace process called the the universal piece that generates peacetime--a formal and calculated state of global peace among participants and their surrounding communities.

The all where the purpose of the universal piece computer is to manage the time machine for peace social invention effort, cooperating and coordinating efforts explicitly in terms of peace.

There are five rules:
0) adopt the lingua franca
1) maintain the universal piece
2) pursue the universal prosperity mission
3) never give up
4) interact voluntarily
5) honor commitments
                                                                                                    

We are all living in a fantasy.

The real question, is which fantasies are least fucked up? That would, like most things, depend on one's perspective. There may not be a satisfactory answer. As the next best thing, we could try be be biased, favoring those fantasies that are most humane, most peaceful, and most practical.

This is a loosely-veiled fantasy sci-fi literary piece, a novel meta-fiction epic. Welcome to the time machine for peace, a social invention program.

Please read on carefully. Our fate as a species depends on it. The Individual needs you.

.
.
.

And so the story goes ...</Text>
